  "text": "## Grafana Query Result Cache Architecture\n\nThe Grafana query result caching layer is implemented as a middleware-based system that intercepts query and resource requests at the plugin backend level. The architecture comprises several key components:\n\n### 1. Cache Middleware (`pkg/services/pluginsintegration/clientmiddleware/caching_middleware.go`)\nThe `CachingMiddleware` class implements `backend.HandlerMiddleware` and intercepts both `QueryData()` and `CallResource()` requests. For each request:\n- It calls `HandleQueryRequest()` to check if results are cached\n- On cache hit, returns cached response immediately\n- On cache miss, executes the actual query and calls `UpdateCacheFn()` to store results\n- Integrates request deduplication to prevent duplicate concurrent requests\n- Records cache performance metrics (hit/miss rates, request duration)\n\n### 2. Cache Key Generation (`pkg/services/caching/service.go`)\nThe `GetKey()` function generates cache keys from query requests:\n- Uses `JSONEncoder` to serialize the entire query request to JSON\n- Applies SHA256 hashing via `SHA256KeyFunc()` to create a deterministic, fixed-length key\n- Prefixes the key with the datasource UID to isolate caches per datasource\n- Format: `{dataSourceUID}:{sha256_hash}`\n\n### 3. Cache Service Interface (`pkg/services/caching/service.go`)\nThe `CachingService` interface defines two core methods:\n- `HandleQueryRequest()`: Checks cache and returns `CachedQueryDataResponse` with optional update function\n- `HandleResourceRequest()`: Similar pattern for HTTP resource requests\n- The OSS implementation (`OSSCachingService`) is a no-op that always returns cache misses (caching is an enterprise feature)\n\n### 4. Cache Backend Abstraction (`pkg/infra/remotecache/remotecache.go`)\nThe `RemoteCache` class provides unified access to different cache backends via the `CacheStorage` interface:\n\n**Supported Backends:**\n- **Redis** (`pkg/infra/remotecache/redis_storage.go`): Uses go-redis client, supports TLS, password auth, connection pooling\n- **Memcached** (`pkg/infra/remotecache/memcached_storage.go`): Uses gomemcache client\n- **Database** (`pkg/infra/remotecache/database_storage.go`): Stores in `cache_data` SQL table with garbage collection every 10 minutes\n\nThe `RemoteCache` wrapper class applies optional decoration layers:\n- **Encryption Wrapper** (`encryptedCacheStorage`): Encrypts cached values using the secrets service\n- **Prefix Wrapper** (`prefixCacheStorage`): Adds a configured prefix to all cache keys for namespace isolation\n\n### 5. Cache Configuration (`pkg/setting/setting_remote_cache.go`)\nThe `RemoteCacheSettings` struct configures cache behavior:\n- `Name`: Cache type (\"redis\", \"memcached\", or \"database\")\n- `ConnStr`: Connection string for Redis/Memcached\n- `Prefix`: Optional key prefix for namespace isolation\n- `Encryption`: Boolean flag to enable encryption of cached values\n- Default TTL is 24 hours (configured in `defaultMaxCacheExpiration` in remotecache.go)\n- Per-query TTL can be overridden via datasource configuration\n\n### 6. Cache Metrics (`pkg/services/pluginsintegration/clientmiddleware/caching_metrics.go`)\nPrometheus histograms track cache performance:\n- `grafana_caching_query_caching_request_duration_seconds`: Query cache request latency\n- `grafana_caching_resource_caching_request_duration_seconds`: Resource cache request latency\n- `grafana_caching_should_cache_query_request_duration_seconds`: Time spent evaluating whether to cache (AWS async queries)\n\n### 7. Request Deduplication Middleware\nThe `requestDeduplicationMiddleware` prevents duplicate concurrent requests using Go's `singleflight.Group`:\n- When N requests execute the same query simultaneously, only 1 query executes\n- Other N-1 requests wait for the first result and use the same response\n- Cache key is derived from datasource UID and query request\n\n### Cache Invalidation Strategy\nThe cache relies on:\n1. **TTL-based expiration**: Cache entries expire after their configured TTL (default 24h, configurable per datasource)\n2. **Explicit deletion**: Individual cache entries can be deleted via `RemoteCache.Delete()` (used when secrets change, etc.)\n3. **Database GC**: For database backend, expired entries are cleaned up every 10 minutes by `databaseCache.internalRunGC()`\n\nNote: Cache invalidation on dashboard save is not explicitly implemented via hooks. Instead, the caching operates at the query execution level - dashboard changes don't automatically invalidate; queries return cached results until expiration. This is the enterprise caching feature design.\n\n### Enterprise vs OSS\n- **OSS**: `OSSCachingService` is always used, which returns cache misses (no-op)\n- **Enterprise**: Enterprise caching service implementations would be provided that actually use the `RemoteCache` backend\n"
}

